Egyptian Stocks: Citadel Capital, Lecico and Mobinil

-- B y   A h m e d   A   N a m a t a l l a
-- 
2011-07-27T13:36:25Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-27/egyptian-stocks-citadel-capital-and-lecico-are-active.html
Egypt ’s benchmark  EGX 30 Index (EGX30) 
dropped for a seventh day, declining 0.7 percent to 5,049.05 at
the 2:30 p.m. close in Cairo.  The following shares rose or fell. Symbols are in
parentheses.  Citadel Capital SAE (CCAP EY) lost 2.2 percent to 4.96
Egyptian pounds, the lowest level in two months. Abraaj Capital
Ltd., a Dubai-based private equity company, dropped plans to
acquire a stake in the Egyptian private-equity firm.  Lecico Egypt SAE (LCSW)   retreated 1.4 percent to 9.6
pounds, the lowest level in three weeks. The Egyptian
manufacturer of tiles and sanitary ware closed a factory in
Alexandria, Egypt until a labor strike is resolved. The factory
produces 30 percent of the company’s sanitary ware, and 74
percent of its tiles, Lecico said.  Egyptian Co. for Mobile Services (EMOB EY) fell for the
ninth day, retreating 1 percent to 104.95 pounds, the lowest
level since October 2008. The Arab country’s second-biggest
mobile network operator, also known as Mobinil, said it had a
second-quarter loss of 108.5 million pounds ($18.2 million)
because of a new tax regime. The median estimate of seven
analysts was for a profit 228 million pounds, according to data
compiled by Bloomberg.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ahmed A Namatalla in Cairo at 
 anamatalla@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
